Vaccination against pneumococcal will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococcal reversed the old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Some voices already, saying that a compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of the free vaccination against pneumococcal peak.
The pharmaceutical institute for vaccines already defines the maximum prices that will pay the insurance.
The experts also clear in the process of vaccination.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for children of August.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated for free against pneumococcal.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If we started vaccination last year or earlier, we will have to pay yourself following vaccinations.
The first dose of vaccine should be administered between the third and the fifth month of the child.
Last year a quarter of families has voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal.
Yet parents paid 1600 crowns or even more for a dose.
The vaccination of younger requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year the insurance spend 300 to 450 000 kroons in doses of vaccine.
However, they save on medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
So far the state spent approximately 500,000 kronor per year for the vaccination of children.
Vaccination repaid was introduced with the "Janota package".
The pneumococcal are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the brain and blood poisoning.
According to surveys in hospitals, there are even 28 deaths of children under 10 years caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced vaccination repaid.
Vaccination will be mandatory?
There is advice on a possible obligation of vaccination in the future.
From January, it must be resolved by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that a compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted the vaccination against pneumococcus.
At an international conference to which our association has participated, experts were not really satisfied with the fact that we have a vaccination optional.
This is not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose at least this.
I think it is a direction that we must now follow said Kalovský.
But the Department of Health does not change the process of vaccination against pneumococcus.
We consider it absolutely not for the moment, "said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
The voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, say doctors.
Hana Cabrnochová, President of the Society specialist paediatricians, recognizes that a vaccine based on the volontariata its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, it could consider a reduction of renewals of vaccinations "In the situation where the vaccine is such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional" said however Cabrnochová.
Experts predict that by next year, more than 80 per cent of new parents will vaccinate their infants.
Vaccination against pneumococcal marks a break from the fact that this is the first vaccination of children which is funded by insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance should free up funds for prevention, they save on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves
This is linked to the concerns of pediatricians practitioners, the purchase of vaccines.
The original intent was to buy vaccines by insurance, doctors receiving the same way as other products of vaccine provided by the state.
Some members were concerned, however, that this would allow insurance to deduct the amounts of health insurance ".
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for the insurance reimburse them.
According to estimates, pediatricians individually invest nearly 40 000 SEK per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
