The results of the tests reveal persistent differences between the races
The federal report last week on the results in mathematics has made a good news for public schools in Washington D.C.
Although the District is still far behind the leading institutions, the report shows that the Grade 4 and Grade 5 (cm1-cm2) are in much greater progress in the past two years that in cities such as Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what is the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (national assessment of progress of education) is the persistent gap between the results of African-Americans and white, both local and national.
The results of white children of Grade 4 (4) to WashingtonD.C. have increased over the last two years, from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500), but those of their classmates African-American increased by three points, 209 to 212.
The gap of success has actually increased between 2007 and 2009, from 53 to 58 points.
The progress of African-Americans in Grade 8 (4th) generally remains constant, falling just one point, 245 to 244.
The result means of whites has not been included in the results of the tests because the sample was not important enough.
The overview over a period of six years is not more encouraging.
In 2003, the gap between blacks and whites in class of Grade 4 (CM1), when the first report NAEP district was published, was 60 points (262 to 202).
Although the results achieved by children in both groups have increased during this period, the difference is only reduced to 58 points.
Last week, some advocates in the District have expressed the concern that rising celebrated by the director of group of educational institutions Michelle A. Rhee and Mayor Adrian M. Fenty (Democrat) were propelled by white students who were already good elements.
This would mean that we have raised the aggregate in considering the elements at the top of the scale, which is problematic and embarrassing, said Jeff Smith, Director of DC Voice, a non-profit group that promotes equality in education in the District.
I do not jump for joy for one or two points earned, "said Kwame R. Brown (related Democrat), Member of the Council of D.C. and whose daughter is in Grade 4, Eaton Elementary (elementary school).
Often critical of the management style of Rhee, Brown said that the message of the results of tests is that the middle schools (colleges) of the city desperately need attention.
Really, you always see the positive signs and I respect that.
But the fear is that we do not spend enough time and energy to our middle schools (colleges).
Rhee said that the District should continue to find better ways to meet the needs of students in difficulty.
This fall, for example, some teachers have been trained to use a new method of reading, the Wilson Reading System, for schoolchildren classes of end of cycle Elementary and early college who does not have integrated the bases of reading earlier in their school and who are lagging behind their peers.
Each day, the mathematics curriculum for grades Kindergarten (Kindergarten to Grade 6 (6th) focuses on the games and the experiences of real life, as they have been put in place in the District by the former superintendent Clifford Janey, who must also be credited to the progress of the NAEP reported last week.
I simply believe that we must continue to work to provide better services to these students below the level of the class, said Rhee.
Others believe that the results of the NAEP raise the question of whether Rhee can continue to raise the overall results of the system while providing money and resources for schools with less good results in order to reduce the gap.
It is a dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a trainer of education at the University of California at Berkeley who is studying the results of the tests of cities.
The conventional political solution is to spend your resources and management reforms to schools located in the poorest neighborhoods of Washington.
Also this targeting may have political repercussions that impede this important program.
But the problem, of course, is that as the other Superintendant schools, she is trying to use the middle class whites and blacks.
We focus to ensure the development of a system of good schools.
We must strengthen our neighbourhood schools so that all families, regardless of where they come from, be assured that their children will be able to obtain an excellent public education.
Janey, now Superintendant schools of Newark, said in an interview this week, that one of the essential elements to reduce the gap of success étaitla duration of traditional public school, today to 180 days in the District of Washington, to compete with the Charter schools.
It must obtain approximately 200 days to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with the union of its teachers last year for 185 days, it considers a "starting point" for even an increase in the next contract.
