It seems that an American missile, which hit along the border with Afghanistan has killed one of the organizers of the operations of Al-Qaida, this week, said Friday the US authorities of counter-intelligence.
If the information is confirmed, it would be the second deadly attack against a terrorist leaders this fall.
Saleh Al-somali was one of two Arab men suspected to have been killed by a pair of missiles in their car, Tuesday, near the town of Miran Shah, in the province of North Waziristan, according to sources and Pakistani authorities in the region.
Local authorities have said that the missiles had been fired by a pilotless aircraft of the type used by the CIA, inside the lawless tribal border of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car, heading towards the Afghan border, when the car was struck, said a member of the secret services Pakistani civilians, speaking by telephone from Miran Shah.
The representatives of the authority said that local activists suspects rushed to place and quickly confiscated what remained of "body completely shredded".
It was completely impossible to local authorities to verify the identity of the victims, but the two U.S. counter-terrorism officials have given evidence not specified that Somali was part of the dead.
Somali was described as one of the organizers of military officials who ran the al-Qaeda terrorist operations of the group outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
Its role was to organize conspiracies around the world, said one of the authorities who wished to remain anonymous, citing the sensitive nature of the air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Given its central role, this included probably conspiracies of attacks against the United States and Europe.
It followed the strategic direction of the leaders of al-Qaeda and has translated into action plans for possible terrorist attacks.
A second representative of the American authority said that Somali had progressed rapidly in the ranks of al-Qaida' and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region.
It is perhaps not known to the general public, but this does not diminish the threat it poses to us and our allies, said the second official representative.
