Gates also wants to calm the anxiety of Kurds concerning the withdrawal pending. The US authorities have quoted Gates saying to Massoud Barzani, President of the Kurdistan Regional Government: "We will preserve your security, your prosperity and your autonomy within a unified Iraq."
We will not abandon you. "
In China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by preaching to the propaganda poster, "The Earth is too tired to accommodate more children" and "A baby as well, it is a grave in more".
They have learned the lesson that the authorities of the Government of Shanghai, alarmed by the rate of birth of their city and the ageing of the population, have radically changed direction this summer and began to encourage young couples to have more than one child; their response has been instantaneous and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and energy to one child.
There is no second, said Wang, age 31, Director of human resources and has a son of 8 months.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one child policy in China, creating two generations of children unique notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, dubbed "little emperors", a crisis of the population threatens the country.
According to the UN, the average birth rate fell from 1.8 children per couple compared to six when the policy was implemented.
The distribution of the population, while it is expected that the number of residents aged 60 and over will explode, 16.7 percent of the population by 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. This figure is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
This imbalance is even worse in the rich coastal cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of the population of residents registered in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, Director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission (Commission of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning) said that the fertile couples to have babies in order "to help reduce the proportion of the aging population and prevent a lack of labour in the future".
Shanghai is on the verge of becoming "too old - but not as rich, however - that developed countries such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual mitigation
Written in the country's constitution in 1978, the Chinese one-child policy is to this day, without doubt, the most controversial requirement introduced by the Communist government.
Couples who violate this policy may have to pay huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and suffer discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have attributed to the police on duty to help the country to avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while the lawyers for human rights have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some representatives of the authority have forced pregnant women a second child to abort.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to a ratio boys - girls abnormally high.
In recent years, the authorities of the population have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they have given more exceptions to the rule - including for residents of cities, members of ethnic minorities and the cases in which the man and woman are already children unique - and in 2007, they have softened much of their slogans hard.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research (Institute of Population Research at Peking University, said that the authorities of the central government recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, the posters encouraging families to have only one child have been replaced by copies of regulations retailer who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples, at home, and slipping leaflets under their door.
He has also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the head of family planning, the response has been disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for records of couples wanting a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115 000 inhabitants, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Officials in Shanghai, disappointed, said that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city, in 2010, is still expected to be only about 165 000 -- slightly higher in 2009 but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the Committee of family planning in the municipality of Caolu of Shanghai, said that the financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to fill their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26 years, said that they loved to have two children and they are legally allowed.
But like many Chinese, they have only the minimum health insurance and life assurance given by the government.
Without a social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
The Western mistakenly see that the one-child policy is a problem of rights, "said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
It is true, we flew the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not only the law.
It is money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, Officer of human resources, said she wanted a single child because it was an itself. "we were the centre of the family and used that everyone cares."
We have not in the habit of taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42 years and owner of a translation company said more bluntly.
For couples working at two, middle class, which reduce the birth rate, he says, it must be selfish pourbien succeed.
The people of 20 or 30 years have grown up seeing their parents fight in the early days of China capitalist and do not want to have themselves this way of life, "he says.
Even one child asks a lot of time his parents, he says.
A mother must abandon at least two years of his social life.
Then there are the problems of space -- "you must change your apartment" -- and planning -- "when your child has only 9 months, you need to write his CV to get a place in the best mother."
Most of his friends are willing to this experience once, said Chen, but not two.
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, "he says.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations group has draft plans for reducing emissions
The climate conference, sponsored by the UN -- characterized so far by assignments disorganized and mutual recriminations -- is back under the spotlight Friday, due to the publication of a document outlining the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations supporting most of the burden, in the coming years.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, stressed the remaining obstacles, as much as it has informed the path to take.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that lack of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Written by a special working group of the United Nations, the text does not say how rich countries would give the poor to withstand the global warming, course and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how the developed economies and emerging economies could reduce their production of carbon and what would be the upper limit of the increase in global temperature that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, Representative àWashington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has written six pages of the document, has studied a text of negotiations of 180 pages to concentrate on what has described the Executive Secretary General on climate change, Yvo de Boer, as "the full picture".
It shows the guidelines of a possible agreement in which the industrial nations reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 percent compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, during the same period, reduced by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations, Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year for the next three years to help poor countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercation occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, Representative of the United States to the negotiating climate has rejected any discussion obliging the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialised countries, compared with the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration becomes harder to China that the Bush administration has been two years ago.
The US will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not focus enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern has made his comments an hour after the Chinese Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs, He Yafei has stated that the US chief negotiator, lacked "common sense", was "extremely irresponsible" for having said earlier in the week that the US would not help financially China to combat global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of major world powers involved, defects emerged both within the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more concerned with the rescue of individual economies that the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States querellant on their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen countries most influential ignore scientific imperatives to act more boldly.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of the reduction of greenhouse gases, even if the vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters accountable for their actions.
It really is a game in which has developed a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, which is also advising on the climate for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to put pressure for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the key participants say that the negotiations will lead to a minimum, a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States which brings together 43 members, has drafted a proposal for a treaty of 24 pages, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of Unit climate of the European Commission, said that the action of small island States has "put political pressure on the political process complete", in part by what they are now unified and they seek to emerging economies such as China and India, to act.
The debates have become a matter of urgency, while delegates focused on the fact that they should solve most of the problems pending before the heads of government come to an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Minister of the Indian environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Vice-Minister descended from their plane and rushed into the building of the Bella Center to attend meetings in camera and conferences of information, in order to make claims that will be reviewed during the course of the next week.
The true image of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people entering and leaving the Palais des Congrès each day -- activists guitar players are nocturnal entertainment mocking of the countries they betray and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by emails -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is increasing: almost all key ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court major, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy of Conservation International.
The lorries arrive.
In Britain, the first train to 225 km / h will redefine the syndrome Monday
A 5h13, Monday morning, a whistle percera night to signal the start of a train that will mark a revolution of transport in Britain.
The first high-speed commuter train the country will reach 225 km / h, whereas it filera of Ashford, in Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Transport Minister, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes aboard the first commuter train Javelin outside London.
He hoped that the new service will allow Britain to integrate an international network of fast trains and reliable and link the large conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The small holes lost suburban cities become successful, durations of business travel will be much less long and the passage of the plane and the car to the train will reduce national emissions of carbon while reducing congestion on roads.
In theory, the three main political parties adhering to this project.
But the ten billion needed to build a new rail network, the battle of planning inevitable and fears of dangers to the environment may curb high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company established in January to achieve for the government a feasibility report, will make his document to Lord Adonis on 30 December.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn in the five metres of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment can be controversial.
In the campaign, the plan will be drawn up to 25 metres of the final itinerary.
It is also expected that HS2 presents three options for a high-speed network larger, towards the north.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred options are put forward in a configuration for which a high-speed line will go up to the West Midlands.
The line split into two at or near Birmingham, with a branch from the west Pennines àManchester and Scotland and another going to the northeast, to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line through Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the best option of performance said a professional of rail.
When this is completed, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first part, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a travel an hour currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel 400km / h, making the British network the fastest in the world.
The original route is designed to allow trains to 400m in length and can carry 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a line London - Birmingham.
A terminal can accommodate 20,000 passengers per hour would be necessary.
Given the constraints of space, it is anticipated that an existing station will be expanded to receive the high-speed network.
The rail industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he feels that the project must be put in place, but public consultations longer and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be taken before a general election.
Even if it launches the machine, the network will be built part by part.
The trains will be forced to drive out of high-speed lines on the existing track north of Birmingham, maintaining journey times between London and Scotland more than three hours.
This solution seems to be the best to ensure passage of aircraft to trains, constituting a reference point for the revolution of rail.
