Road: three marathons for an agreement that saves the supply of Christmas
After three sessions of marathon talks, the road sector unions and employers' organisation TLF, only to be stayed until the end, arrived Friday evening in an agreement that puts an end to the strike and the threat to the supply of Christmas.
At the meeting of signatures Friday evening, the secretary of state for transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "delighted" of this agreement, after several rounds of negotiations, which began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions the negotiators were left in the early morning Friday, with the hope of signing quickly in late morning the text of the agreement.
And even if three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took more than six hours of a meeting began at 11.00 so that everyone is agreed, and that at 6 p.m. the text is signed.
The conflict "would have been very damaging for business" and "it was feared that it will disrupt the holidays for years," said Mr Bussereau.
The text provides for a wage increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and euro2.9% for the highest (international transport).
In hourly rate, for the bas-salaires, ” is 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It is not much, but it is very far, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
This is will give the order to our supporters that there are no barriers, no blockade of centres of supplies.
But we can always have some holdouts who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, President of TLF, welcomed "a good agreement", even if it was "difficult to concede the increases on the high salaries given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be of the order of EUR 170 monthly for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is the agreement of common sense and the respect of employees, "said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) has welcomed" a historic agreement ".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) has raised "an acceptable compromise."
The agreement also provides for the upgrading of the travel expenses of 3%, and the holding of general state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will help to address the issue of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a decrease of EUR 100 million in employers' contributions" was the subject of a Government amendment to the bill amending finance for 2009, voted in Thursday night on Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "in terms identical".
The signing of TLF provides that the agreement applies to the member companies to this organization, and in a second time, the entire profession, in the case of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be "as soon as possible," assured Mr Bussereau.
The opposition of employers' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "fool" because the EUR 100 million "had already been promised to the sector to offset a portion of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport has forced us to negotiate in the urgency, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but not to thwart the eaters of turkey next partying, has deplored the Unostra.
For the Ur, the agreement risk "digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
