The Turkish courts dissolved the pro-Kurdish party, decision consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday the dissolution of the main pro-Kurdish party in the country, a decision that was immediately followed by expressions of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is to reach out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "home of activities prejudicial to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said the press the President of the Court Hasim Kiliç, at the end of four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously of 11 judges, while a qualified majority of 37 votes was required to give the dissolution, said Mr Kiliç, adding that party officials, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from politics for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Mrs Tugluk and confiscation by the Treasury assets of the party.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MEPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP to obey "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organisation by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the showcase legal policy of PKK rebels.
The party assured, however, that there was "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with him.
The verdict of the Court comes at a time when the government is to reach out to the Kurdish community in proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, to try to stem the support of the PKK and put an end the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP had said that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in the south-east Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
After the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered at the premises of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the largest city in southeast populated by majority Kurds.
The security forces fired tear gas and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or stones, with slingshots.
About 100 people demonstrated also in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of Justice would "deepen the despair".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish, night-glasses) by banning a party, "he said to the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This does not resolve, "said Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total torpedoing of democratic openness launched by the government, commented on the political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction of the PKK, he added.
Thursday, the PKK has claimed an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in the north of Turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
The new "Silicon-valley"
For a long time it had the reputation of city secret, prohibited to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was under the Soviet regime, a place of research secret arms, under strict supervision.
Today, with its 216 000 inhabitants to 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the "Silicon Valley" Soviet.
Important places of production and research in micro- and nanoelectronics are located.
By September 2008 representatives of Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, place of science francfortois - with university institutes and societies in the centre of innovations in Frankfurt (FIZ).
There have been meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg have ratified a protocol of close collaboration.
The signatories were the Deputy Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwartz section chief project for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific Exchange
It is a scientific exchange sustainable.
But also of economic relations.
It will allow companies FIZ to enter the Russian market in full expansion.
Unlike the Russian scientific societies to obtain contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of research institutes and companies Soviet famous.
There is the Institute of Electrical Engineering from Moscow, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The municipality was founded in 1958 as "socialist planned city" for research into weapons.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") gets its name from the forested hills in the heart of which research centres are located.
The project S21: a brake for Stuttgart
We cannot place high enough the magnitude of the project Stuttgart 21.
To its supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe".
If we want. S21, it is more that the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, in a chaos despairing of shipyards for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 is born of the spirit of the 1980s.
The stations head line, with routes which terminated in full-throated city, had a reputation at the time to be the relics of the art of transport in the 19th century who were effect of brake shoe modern rail traffic because it was once a lot of time to get the locomotives back to the front.
Arrival, stopping short, departure – that is what needed to be done.
That is why the stations head of line must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And Stuttgart also: a station of trains, which is about halfway on the major trans-European rail between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava where the slogan "heart of Europe".
The project S21 will really start, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners have recognized that the cost to bury the station in the capitals of Hesse and Bavaria, was exorbitant.
Indeed, the head of line stations no longer pose real problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with railcars and voiture-pilote at both ends.
However, it is now the achievement of Stuttgart 21 next to the new route of the line inter-city towards Ulm.
The regional and communal prevailed.
The company of railways is in part because it is the taxpayer who makes the cost of the risks of the largest infrastructure project of the Federal Republic and not the public company.
From the point of view planning this project is relatively well justified.
There is an urban space which – if the graphs of planners generated by computer – will be very green.
For the system of rail transport the S21 is harmful.
The station of passage and the enlargement of the section are designed for human trafficking which attributed - and this is typical of the 1980s - an enormous growth.
At the time there was not yet competition from cheap flights.
The policy of modern traffic should first concentrate on strengthening the traffic of goods transport by rail is much more environmentally friendly than by truck on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious indirectly affects many other rail projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the draft of the Bolzano.
It is the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion are more realistic.
One thing is sure, in the next decade this money will for other junction and congestion in the network.
The list of the Department of Transport mentioned in all 60 major projects.
One of the most important is the enlargement of the section across the Rhine Valley of 180 good kilometres.
Since 1987 this line is built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent support here to build on the fungus.
But the project S21 is the effect of a brake shoe.
The itinerary of the Rhine Valley is becoming the bottleneck of international freight traffic, and this in the heart of Europe.
