Cleansing in university studies
Partial success for students: After a year of strike educational Ministers of Education and Cultural Affairs of the Länder decide to be more conciliatory: At a meeting between Ministers and delegates to the Conference of Presidents, an agreement has been developed stipulating that the working conditions of students Bachelor and Master should be improved.
In the future, students should be able to overcome their studies.
They are particularly put accordpour to lighten the weight of reviews: a single examination is expected to close the module of study chosen.
In addition, the workload will be reconsidée proportions to ensure "realistic and acceptable".
The political authorities and institutions of higher education wish to facilitate the recognition of examinations between universities and abroad.
The Länder have also committed to organise common structural requirements more flexible for the vocational Bachelor and Master.
At the regional level, there should be no different regulation of a Land to another.
Less reviews
Since the beginning of the student protests last June, the Minister of Education of the Länder and the university rectors have repeatedly to the mouth the buzzword: "Étudiabilité".
But for the first time, this expression seems to take a practical meaning.
The accreditation council decided to slash the number of some reviews: "Each module should normally be concluded by a single review ", in a document of thirty pages on future conditions for admission to university cycles.
Reinhold Grimm, Chairman of the Board of Certification says that by sharply reducing the burden of reviews should be able to stop the slippage, which interfered considerably to the étudiabilité.
The "étudiabilité" should also be, in the future, the decisive criterion of the organization of studies.
The modules like the substance must be examined carefully to see if we cannot avoid this smothering sensation that there is sometimes in the choice of courses.
Hamburg / Berlin -
Students should "have the opportunity and the flexibility to allow and encourage the personal initiative".
The new regulation will affect access to new university cycles but will also be adapted to existing cycles.
These cycles must be "réaccrédités" every 5 years, which means, however, that it was only in 2015 that all cycles have been examined.
There are 10 relevant accreditation agencies throughout the federal territory that depend on
In October, the Ministers of Education had exerted some pressure on the Länder to weigh on the agencies so that the programmes are not too loaded and the regime of reviews not too strict.
In some Länder, universities and graduate schools have already agreed with their regional departments to take the appropriate measures.
