More than a footnote on Herta Müller
It is by these words "Arrival in Germany and it is a beautiful, almost more control..." that begins a work of the poet Werner Söllner, in which he dealt with in snippets of disturbing sentences, the experiences of a dissident arrived in Germany who won freedom but lost at the same time its linguistic territory.
Werner Söllner, born in 1951 in Banat in Romania, was first professor of German and English in Bucharest and, subsequently, director of collection in a publishing house for youth before moving to Frankfurt am Main.
Söllner received several literary prizes; in 1993 he was the Chair very popular poetry of the Goethe University in Frankfurt and since 2002 it is director of the forum of literature in Hesse to the house of artist of Mousonturm in Frankfurt.
He has done a lot of him in circles not literary last Tuesday, at a conference in Munich, whose theme was "The German literature in Romania in the mirror and the distorting mirror of your Securitate files".
Visibly upset and embarrassed, Söllner made a statement in which he acknowledged to his fellow writers germano-roumains as Richard Wagner, William Totok, Franz Hodjak, and Helmuth Frauendorfer that he had worked as an informant for the Securitate police policy.
Söllner received in 1989 the price of the German language together with some of the participants.
The trials of enrolment insidiously began in 1971.
I am, "Söllner" therefore someone who has not sufficiently stood auxessais intimidation of the Securitate. "
The poet Werner Söllner is the informant Walter (MI Walter).
Almost simultaneously with the honoration Nobel Prize for Herta Müller and its best literary trouble with the mechanisms of power of the dictatorship, the literary scene is shaken and in particular the community of German authors from Romania, a case that clearly shows the abyss and baseness of a political system, based on police surveillance and espionage.
Werner Söllner is, as far as we can tell from the current knowledge, not only guilty but also victim.
In his own Securitate file, IM Walter has played a role, the specialist literature Michael Markel after the confession of Söllner and it refers to the positive influence of IM Walter who had intervened in its favour.
"He had been drawn from all difficult situations at the time," according to Markel.
Markel has felt the need moralde make this comment.
The form in which Söllner made his statement and before the public was unexpected, however the confession of a former dissident of its collaboration with the Romanian secret services is in fact, not so surprising.
Germany is a reserve for the spies of the Securitate had already written Herta Müller in July in the newspaper Die Zeit, having read the 914 pages of his own record.
It can be assumed that the victims have made speculation and will sometimes guessed what real names were hiding last names of borrowing Sorin, Voicu and Walter.
Unlike Germany, where between the consultation of the Stasi files is a reliable process, the attitude to the legacy of the Securitate files is still very confused.
A systematic clarification was constantly frustrated and slowed in past years.
It was only in 1999 that a National Council for the institution Birthler was created to work on the assimilation of the Securitate Archives (CNSAS) but the return of files has rather dragged since.
Since 2005 there is a law that defines the management of archives.
The influence of former members of the Securitate in Romania is still very great, is confirmed by an interview with a former head of the Securitate of Temesvar which, after the announcement of the award of the Nobel Prize to Herta Müller, expressed in a very dismissive of the winner.
She had a psychosis, and ultimately we had questioned only once.
The infamy of power was intending to speak here, without any gene, under the guise of freedom of expression.
Of course, many questions inevitable are associated with the case Söllner as happens so often in a context of guilt hidden.
Why now? Who has been despoiled? The weighted reaction listeners, the admission of Söllner, offered hope that the rest of this chapter will be defined more by a thirst for knowledge that by accusations and a sense of shame.
On the genesis of the work of Herta Müller, who received the Nobel Prize yesterday, it is more than a footnote.
