The case Kunduz
Frontal attack opposition: the head of the parliamentary group of the Greens, Jürgen Trittin, accused the Ministry of Defence Guttenberg of lying in the case of the case Kunduz.
The SPD party and The Left Party (Die Linke) ask the Chancellor explanations.
Hamburg / Berlin - After review of the latest information on the air attack Kunduz, the opposition has criticized the Minister of Defence Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg (CSU) délibérémentdissimulé some facts.
The Minister has intentionally "made an untruth" on the deadly strike two tankers last September, said the head of the parliamentary group of the Greens, Jürgen Trittin, Saturday during the broadcast of information of the chain ARD "Tagesschau" (the newspaper pm).
Clearly, this means that he lied.
The order to kill has been given in total disregard of the rules of the International Security Assistance Force in Afghanistan (ISAF).
It is, in essence, the content of the report available to NATO and which was read by Mr Guttenberg, said Trittin.
Last Friday, according to new revelations of the media, the objective of lafrappe was in reality, not to destroy the stolen trucks, but was intended to eliminate two major Taliban leaders.
According to the investigation report of NATO, 142 people were killed or injured in the US air attack, which was launched at the request of the German colonel Goerg Klein, military commander of Kunduz.
The Greens, the SPD and the Left have asked Saturday the Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU), to vote as soon as possible before the federal Parliament and reveal what Guttenberg really knew about the incident.
Jürgen Trittin and his colleague from the Green Party Renate Künast are of the opinion that Mrs Angela Merkel must say clearly whether the strategy of targeted killing is part of the Government's Afghan policy fédéralet if the Chancery, the army and intelligence services have approved the new strategy.
The government spokesman categorically rejects the criticism.
The Chancery has in no way influenced the interventions of the army in Afghanistan, he said.
Saturday, voices were increasingly strong to express doutesquant the real reasons the removal of the Inspector General Wolfgang Schneiderhan and Secretary of State Peter Wichert, as had been presented by the department.
According to the information in the newspaper SPIEGEL, the information they had handed over to Guttenberg concerning the attack tankers were both correct and complete.
Officially, they would have concealed the existence of the report of NATO and hid the Minister some details troublesome.
In the entourage of two senior officials it suggests, however, that they have informed the Ministry of Defence of the existence of several reports, including a document of two pages of Colonel Klein and a report of the military police.
The Frankfurter Allgemeiner Sonntagszeitung reported that Wichert have meanwhile requested in a letter a clarification of the facts.
So far, it has not received a response
Saturday, the Department did not wish to comment on the allegations and referred to the committee of inquiry of the federal Parliament would be the next Wednesday to render the light on the facts in question.
The worlds of dream
Some see, while awake, images and hear voices that nobody else sees or hears.
It is not only among the mental patients, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between fantasy and reality mingle.
As these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is going very well.
When we are lying in our rooms clouded, we can do without hindrance to the dreams and wildest fantasies.
However, awake, the experience of dream, hear and see things that others do not perceive, has the reputation in the Western world to be mad or drugged, or at least to be an original.
Such images and voices do not appear in the mental ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is in question: it is the same neuronal activity that allows us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, but sometimes prompts the boundaries between the dream, madness and reality to melt.
A state of arousal aware, taking the form of a dream, may be in various forms, in the best of cases this is called visions, at worst madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect is distinguished, visions of the mystique Hildegard von Bingen, the experiences of drugs of the prophet of the New Age Carlos Castaneda, the latter statements of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to process very similar.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, substances neurotransmitter brain - first and foremost the dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and Achétylcholine - breaks and that the interaction between the different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during a schizophrenic psychosis.
The force of attraction land has more power on the person.
Since antiquity, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between the madness and the dream.
For Aristotle, hallucinations, were a form of Rêve-éveillé; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of the modern psychiatry, found in 1861 "a great similarity between the madness and the dream," Sigmund Freud the dream was "a psychosis with all irregularities, imagination, delusions and illusions sensory who composed".
We are in autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into character of a comic strip.
His body is in two dimensions to the garish colours.
The attraction of land has more power over him, there is the wave of the ceiling.
He feels a coup.
Behind him creatures of devil ailées, grimaçantes, his mouth bloodied, showing teeth.
They continue, give him kicking with heavy boots ablaze, the cast against the walls, he feels pain throughout the body.
A thundering voice, nasty, howl, leaving the walls and the radio.
It can no longer bear those voices who insult and humiliate.
Henning T. pulling two cables of its stereo, in fact a loop and attached to a hook attached to the ceiling.
It gets on a baffle and happens the loop around the neck.
It jumps.
The loop stands out.
That you should serve as a lesson, shout the voice in a chorus to extract the tympanum. "Is in a clinic and fais-toi treat!"
Today Henning T. 40 years ago, he lived six acute psychosis, the last date of 2 years, the first in nearly 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: Psychosis schizo-affective, paranoid, furthermore it is maniaco-dépressif, he takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he is married for three years.
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
The illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers at least once in her life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics that is the most common illness after the depression.
In a crisis of schizophrenia, people can no longer tell the difference between the inside and the outside world, they are in a state of hyper excitation, that they may suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voice command, who comment on or dialogue.
The optical hallucinations are not rare.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the trivial, the brain can no longer filter the disruptive signals, the conscious is drowned under the sensations.
Just as the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies outcome of deeper layers of conscience.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the issue, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the Department of Psychiatry CHU Heidelberg (Allgemeine Psychiatry im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is located in the centre of the situation, meaning focused on him.
At the same time it is reflected in a passive role, it is like a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
That is why the schizophrenia often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the possibility to adjust the reality, the illusions are a cruel reality, wake up is excluded.
To experience once in her life of a hallucination.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is seen during the psychosis is fundamentally conserved."
The thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of lived in a real framework.
Why does our brain this kind of antics, is still a mystery to researchers.
Exceptional situations can bring everyone to momentarily lose the perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determinants.
The researchers speculate that the persons concerned are tiny brain damage.
It is assumed that the neural maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, "says Fuchs.
But what remains unexplained is how the anomaly of the system occurs and also the fact that it is not for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger of psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly the hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on the neurotransmitters.
When our brain heats.
This is crazy, "said Professor of Psychology Erich Kasten of Lübeck is that the suffering of their hallucinations and psychotic take expensive drugs to undo while others buy drugs expensive to obtain it.
The perception pleasant or unpleasant illusions is often just a matter of perspective.
Kasten brings together for ten years reports of hallucinations and the phenomena of images illusory: Last year he published its findings in a book entitled "The unreal world in our head."
The hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical psychoses but also an impressive number of many other diseases.
They include psychological problems such as borderline or depression but also the migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or the head trauma.
It is surprising that in certain conditions even the brain of healthy people is subject to hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They form when the areas of the brain that deal with the sensory perceptions are hyperactives or not sufficiently refrénées; when our brain heats but also when there is lack of stimulation.
The drugs can trigger this state as a brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimulus, stress, the pessimists of love or other mental states exceptional.
In recent studies, one third of participants acknowledged having made at least once in their life experience a hallucination.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. 16 years ago, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania and she goes to the school.
A young girl to normal indeed.
If there was not the images and voices.
During the recess, a young boy, thin, with long hair chestnut, send him the floor.
When she replied his comrades watch, surprised - nobody else sees or hears this boy.
They believe that this girl is a lunatic but Sarah K do not dream, it is certain.
She is awake, hears and sees the boy as she sees and hears the girl who is sitting next to her on the bench.
It can even see its presence temporarily.
It is a good feeling, she found this young sympathetic.
Am I mad?, wondered sometimes.
But she knows that this young and other visions are not real and they will disappear again.
The night appearances are, in general, frightening.
Often the visions are cumbersome.
When it is in the classroom, sometimes it can follow the course because the teacher is just being present a new student in his eyes and ears when it is invisible to others and that the professor is clearly trying to explain the equations in Table.
The night appearances are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of his bedroom, it expects sleep that came too little and too late, it often cannot make the distinction if she is awake or dream already, if the images she sees, faces grimaçants or the girl with bloody cuts on his arms and legs are before his eyes open or closed.
Let me quiet, Cree it to these creatures.
It does not mention or to his parents or his friends, they would take to a mad.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. has now 20 years.
She had her car last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago the hallucinations have ceased.
Since it came into contact by Internet with the psychologist Kasten she knows very well that it is not crazy.
The madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough incentives, the likelihood is that it has hallucinations after a certain time.
I assume that the brain is not busy enough, ensures that there is animation.
Sarah K., single girl, was afraid of other children when she was small and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when she learned to 13 years, that the man she called Dad, since it was in age to think, was not his real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active in the acoustic and visual hallucinations, and for the impressions and actual noise, it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to differentiate between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten "takes place in the brain, the reality is formed from there.
The hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real. "
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenic, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that the fantasies are not real images.
That is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish the hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only a step between the dream and the hallucination.
In our world too focused on the conscience has unfortunately quickly tend to take the imaginary experiences for diseases, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor at Heidelberg and doctor leader of the clinic psychiatry and psychotherapy hospital Florence Nightingale in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious disease, painful but which also contains something positive, creator - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-degenhard has studied the form of so-called oniroïde experience, a particular form of the modification of the conscience stirred by the dream.
The experienced oniroïdes are very complex semi-rêves which are perceived as real by the lives and that it cannot differentiate the dream even when it is in a state of arousal.
The state of consciousness oniroïde occurs during a trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathie which fully aware, experience paralysis engine.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of itself and the world, due to a total inability and sustainable to move, it replaces the real situation which affects his life, by his own imaginary world which is divorced from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between the dream and the hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, a form of means and interpretation, in a situation in itself intolerable, a capacity of organisation that is given to men, not to sink into the void of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurichois Peter Cornelius Classen, art historian also describes his experiences oniroïdes in his book "change of heart" as action to safeguard the soul.
He was 49 years, when his conscious part for a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is condemned to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges in a world that it has created from scratch, visit places foreign travel in time. It is old man bed in a sanatorium rail, a robot to ensure his mind on his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages of noble who manufacture drugs based on blood.
It is removed by a Greek Moto who takes in his country, he surfing with his hospital bed in the firn Alps and meeting a Korean mafia.
It absorbs completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen these domestic trips are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different, he wrote in describing what he lived.
Instead of dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this lived detonated the horizon of our other everyday experiences, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, the delusions oniroïdes, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how our representations of external reality are fragile, even in a state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
